    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>star rating</strong> is a 1-to-5 scale numerical score aggregated from user reviews of a product, service, or business. In search, star ratings appear in two ways: as <strong>rich snippets</strong> in organic results (via Schema.org AggregateRating markup) and as review scores in the Google Local Pack and Maps (sourced from Google Business Profile reviews). Both forms significantly increase click-through rates and influence purchase decisions.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Local SEO / Reviews</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Review Stars, Rating Stars</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">7 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Star ratings are among the highest-impact, lowest-cost click-through optimisations available to any website or local business. A listing with visible yellow stars in search results stands out in a page of plain blue links — and consumers overwhelmingly trust and act on review scores before making decisions.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a star rating?</h2>
        <p>A star rating is the visual representation of an aggregated review score. The 5-star scale is the most common format across the web — used by Google, Amazon, Yelp, TripAdvisor, and thousands of individual websites. The score is typically calculated as the arithmetic mean (average) of all submitted ratings, sometimes weighted by recency or reviewer reputation.</p>
        <p>In the context of search and local SEO, star ratings serve two distinct functions:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Rich snippets in organic search.</strong> Using Schema.org structured data, websites can mark up their reviews so Google displays yellow star icons alongside the search result. This applies to product pages, recipe pages, course pages, and certain other content types where the site hosts reviews.</li>
          <li><strong>Google Business Profile ratings.</strong> For physical businesses, Google aggregates ratings left directly on Google Maps and displays them in the Local Pack, the Knowledge Panel, and Google Maps search results.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>The two systems are separate: a website's Schema.org markup does not feed into the business's Google Maps rating, and vice versa.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">CTR impact</div>
          <p>Pages with star rating rich snippets consistently show higher click-through rates than equivalent listings without stars. Across multiple industry studies, the uplift ranges from <strong>15% to 30% higher CTR</strong> for results with visible star ratings, with the effect strongest for results in positions 2-5 where visual differentiation matters most.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why star ratings matter for SEO and conversions</h2>
        <p>The business case for managing star ratings sits at the intersection of search performance and consumer psychology.</p>

        <h3>Search click-through rates</h3>
        <p>In a SERP full of uniform text links, a result with yellow stars immediately draws the eye. Eye-tracking studies show that SERP users fixate on stars before reading surrounding text. Higher CTR from the same ranking position signals to Google that your result is more relevant — which can compound into ranking improvements over time.</p>

        <h3>Local Pack ranking</h3>
        <p>For local businesses, Google's Local Pack ranking algorithm explicitly considers review signals — both the quantity of reviews and the average rating. Google states that "high-quality, positive reviews from your customers will improve your business's visibility" in local results. A business with 200 reviews at 4.6 stars will typically outperform a competitor at the same location with 20 reviews at 3.8 stars.</p>

        <h3>Purchase conversion</h3>
        <p>The Spiegel Research Center found that displaying reviews increases conversion rates by 270% for lower-priced products and over 380% for higher-priced products. Consumers use star ratings as a trust shortcut — a quick signal that others have validated the quality of what they are about to buy.</p>

        <h2 id="rich-snippets">How to get star ratings in Google search results</h2>
        <p>For organic (non-local) search results, star ratings appear through Schema.org structured data. The two most relevant schema types are:</p>

        <h3>AggregateRating schema</h3>
        <p>Used when you have collected multiple reviews and want to display the average. Appropriate for product pages, business listings, apps, and books.</p>
        <div class="url-flow">
          "aggregateRating": &#123;<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;"@type": "AggregateRating",<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;"ratingValue": "4.7",<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;"reviewCount": "143",<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;"bestRating": "5",<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;"worstRating": "1"<br>
          &#125;
        </div>

        <h3>Review schema</h3>
        <p>Used for a single review of an item. Can be nested inside Product, Book, Movie, or other schemas. Can be combined with AggregateRating on the same page.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Google's eligibility restrictions</div>
          <p>Google only shows review rich snippets for specific content types: products, recipes, software apps, courses, and a few others. It does not show stars for local business homepages, employment listings, or general service pages — even if you add valid AggregateRating markup. For local businesses, review stars come from Google Business Profile, not Schema.org markup.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="local-stars">Star ratings for local businesses</h2>
        <p>Local business star ratings in Google Maps and the Local Pack come exclusively from Google reviews — not from your website's Schema.org markup, not from other platforms like Yelp or Trustpilot.</p>
        <p>The rating displayed in the Local Pack is the straight average of all Google reviews your business has received, typically rounded to one decimal place. The number of reviews shown alongside it is the total count of reviews.</p>
        <p>Google's local ranking documentation confirms that review signals (rating and quantity) are among the factors that influence Local Pack positioning. Businesses actively managing their review programme — generating new reviews, responding to all reviews — consistently outperform those that do not in local visibility metrics.</p>

        <h2 id="what-makes-good">What makes a good star rating?</h2>
        <p>Counter-intuitively, a perfect 5.0 rating can hurt conversions. Research from the Spiegel Research Center and Northwestern University shows the "sweet spot" is between 4.2 and 4.5 stars:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Ratings below 3.5 suppress click-through and conversion significantly</li>
          <li>Ratings of 3.5-4.0 are considered acceptable but not compelling</li>
          <li>Ratings of 4.0-4.5 show the strongest purchase intent correlation</li>
          <li>Ratings of 4.5-4.9 remain very strong but slightly lower purchase intent than 4.0-4.5</li>
          <li>A perfect 5.0 is perceived as suspicious — suggesting fake or insufficient reviews</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The psychological reasoning: consumers expect some negative experiences and look for authentic reviews. A perfect score with only 3 reviews is less trustworthy than a 4.3 score with 150 reviews.</p>

        <h2 id="review-generation">How to generate more star ratings</h2>
        <p>The volume of reviews matters as much as the average rating. Here are the most effective approaches for generating authentic review volume:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Ask at the right moment.</strong> Request a review at the point of peak satisfaction — immediately after a successful delivery, resolved support ticket, or positive follow-up check-in. Timing is the biggest variable in review generation.</li>
          <li><strong>Make the path frictionless.</strong> Provide a direct link to your Google review form. Every additional click reduces completion rates significantly.</li>
          <li><strong>Embed review links in post-purchase emails.</strong> Automated post-purchase sequences requesting reviews are the highest-volume review generation method for e-commerce.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond to all reviews.</strong> Google's guidelines note that responding to reviews signals engagement and can influence future reviewers. Businesses that respond publicly to negative reviews often see those reviews updated to higher ratings.</li>
          <li><strong>Never offer incentives for reviews.</strong> Both Google and the FTC prohibit incentivised reviews. Offering discounts, gifts, or other benefits for reviews violates platform policies and can result in listing suspension.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common star rating mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Using AggregateRating on pages with no real reviews.</strong> Google penalises review markup that does not reflect genuine user-submitted ratings.</li>
          <li><strong>Marking up self-assessments.</strong> Marking up your own opinion of your product or service as an AggregateRating is a policy violation.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring negative reviews.</strong> An unanswered 1-star review on your Google Business Profile is visible to every potential customer who finds you in Maps. Public responses demonstrate professionalism and context.</li>
          <li><strong>Review gating.</strong> Filtering which customers are invited to leave reviews based on their expected sentiment (e.g., only asking happy customers) violates Google's review policies and can lead to listing penalties.</li>
          <li><strong>Treating star rating as a one-time task.</strong> Review recency matters. A business with 500 reviews but none in the last year looks inactive.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="best-practices">Best practices for star ratings in 2026</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Implement AggregateRating schema on all eligible product and service pages</strong> using JSON-LD in the page head. Test with Google's Rich Results Test tool.</li>
          <li><strong>Set a review generation goal.</strong> Aim to receive at least one new review per week for local businesses, or one per 20 purchases for e-commerce.</li>
          <li><strong>Monitor your ratings weekly.</strong> Use Google Business Profile notifications and a reputation management tool to catch negative reviews quickly.</li>
          <li><strong>Respond within 24 hours</strong> to all reviews — positive and negative. The response is public and shapes how potential customers perceive your business culture.</li>
          <li><strong>Track the CTR impact.</strong> In Google Search Console, compare CTR for pages with star rich snippets vs equivalent pages without. This quantifies the revenue impact of your review programme.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
        <div class="faq-list">
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
