            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Star ratings appear in Google search results through two mechanisms: (1) Schema.org structured data (Review or AggregateRating markup) embedded in a page's HTML, which Google may render as yellow stars in organic search snippets. (2) Google Business Profile reviews, which show as stars in the Local Pack, Maps, and the Knowledge Panel for local businesses.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What star rating does Google require to show rich snippets?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Google does not specify a minimum star rating to display rich snippets. However, the AggregateRating schema requires a minimum ratingCount (Google recommends at least a few reviews) and the rating must be on a defined scale. Google reserves the right not to show rich snippets even with valid markup.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Do star ratings affect SEO rankings directly?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Star ratings do not directly influence organic ranking algorithms for standard web results. However, they have a strong indirect effect: pages with star rich snippets earn higher click-through rates (studies show 15-30% CTR uplift), and higher CTR may positively influence rankings. For local SEO, review count and average rating are confirmed Google Business Profile ranking factors.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Can I add star ratings to my website without real reviews?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. Google's structured data guidelines prohibit self-serving reviews and require star ratings to reflect genuine user opinions. Marking up editorial content or self-assessed quality scores as AggregateRating is a policy violation. Google may manually penalise sites that misuse review markup.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is a good average star rating?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Research from Spiegel Research Center shows that products with ratings between 4.2 and 4.5 out of 5 convert best — a perfect 5.0 is actually perceived as suspicious. For local businesses, a rating above 4.0 is generally considered good, and ratings below 3.5 significantly suppress click-throughs and conversions.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

